'''Pamela Ann Mary Flood''' (born 1971) is an [[Irish people|Irish]] television presenter and former [[Model (person)|model]] from [[Tallaght]], [[South Dublin]]. She received the [[Miss Ireland]] crown in 1993. An employee of [[Raidi<U+00F3> Teilif<U+00ED>s <U+00C9>ireann]], she is a well-recognised face on the broadcaster's television channels, having presented ''[[Off the Rails (TV series)|Off the Rails]]'', ''[[Marry Me (TV series)|Marry Me]]'' and ''[[The Podge and Rodge Show]]''. She also made an appearance in the [[genealogy]] series ''[[Who Do You Think You Are? (Irish TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]]'', learning that her grandmother was an illegitimate child and that a deceased distant relative was accused of murdering her husband, but later found not guilty - over 160 years ago. She then went on to feature on ''[[Showhouse|Celebrity Showhouse]]'' broadcast on 29 December 2008.

==Career==
Flood worked as a continuity officer with national broadcaster RT<U+00C9> from 1997<U+2013>2000, and was a presenter of Irish fashion television show ''Off the Rails'' for a number of years before receiving the axe <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/the-matriarchs-of-montrose-1510015.html|title=The matriarchs of Montrose|date=2008-10-25|accessdate=2008-11-02|publisher=''[[Irish Independent]]''}}</ref> in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/fashion-beauty/a-stylish-match-1474828.html|title=A stylish match|date=2008-09-13|accessdate=2008-11-02|publisher=''[[Irish Independent]]''}}</ref> Flood moved on to ''Marry Me'', of which there were eight editions,<ref>[http://www.rte.ie/tv/marryme/index.html ''Marry Me'']. RT<U+00C9>. Accessed 2 November 2008.</ref> and has also presented two editions of ''The Podge and Rodge Show'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/the-bourne-supremacy-1510144.html|title=The Bourne Supremacy|date=2008-10-25|accessdate=2008-11-02|publisher=''[[Irish Independent]]''}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/budget-2009/analysis-overview/return-of-the-hairshirt-1499038.html|title=Return of the hairshirt|date=2008-10-15|accessdate=2008-11-02|publisher=''[[Irish Independent]]''}}</ref> For her research in the RT<U+00C9> series ''Who Do You Think You Are?'', she travelled through 19th-century Dublin, taking in red light districts, millionaire solicitors, pawnbrokers, contested wills, illegitimate children and murder. She met historian David Nolan, who has written a history of Corballis House, where her granny was sent to stay and subsequently discovered the illegitimacy of her existence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/16-blocks-1496279.html|title=16 Blocks|date=2008-10-11|accessdate=2008-11-02|publisher=''[[Irish Independent]]''}}</ref> She appeared on the front cover of the ''[[RT<U+00C9> Guide]]'' to promote the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/news-gossip/rte-should-prepare-to-stretch-the-boundaries-1475262.html|title=RTE should prepare to stretch the boundaries|date=2008-09-14|accessdate=2008-09-21|publisher=''[[Irish Independent]]''}}</ref> An appearance on ''[[Anonymous (TV series)|Anonymous]]'' as "Doreen Prendergast".<ref>[http://www.rte.ie/tv/anonymous/2007_ep04.html Pamela Flood on ''Anonymous'']</ref>

==Personal life==
In 2008, Flood announced the recent end of her three-year relationship with Michael Sharp, the manager of Denis Desmond's ''Spirit'' nightclub in Dublin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rteguide.ie/2008/0322/staroftheday.html|title=Star of the Day|date=2008-03-22|accessdate=2008-11-02|publisher=[[RT<U+00C9> Guide]]}}</ref> She then began a new one with restaurateur, Ronan Ryan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/around-town/has-pamela-found-true-love-1429645.html|title=Has Pamela found true love?|date=2008-07-08|accessdate=2008-11-02|publisher=''[[Evening Herald]]''}}</ref><ref>{{option=com_content&task=view&id=1468&Itemid=10107&ed=124|title=Producers Looking for Waterford People to Propose in new RT<U+00C9> Programme|date=2007-11-07|accessdate=2008-11-02|publisher=''[[Waterford Today]]''}}</ref>

